Iron fortress is a pretty straightforward card that provides defensive scaling. It's pretty much footwork stapled to a metallicize, which is probably worse then just footwork due to the cost increase (and the upgrade not providing more dex). With that being said, it's still an important piece of the puzzle for late game champ, which is notoriously their hardest part of the game, and you are usually pretty happy to have 2-3 of these by that point. Champ's skill bonuses naturally incentivize playing many cheap skills, and a fair number of those will block and scale well with the dexterity, so you usually don't need to work very hard to get some synergies going here (circumvent being one of the better synergies, since it can dig you into more cheap block cards, like an off brand backflip). 

Even if Iron fortress is a little worse than many other characters defensive scaling options, you still should be putting a high priority on it, because there just aren't that many other options available to you. Unless you find some way to very consistently enter and exit defensive stance, you will likely need iron fortress to cover your late game mitigation needs. Your early game is also so overwhelmingly strong that it usually won't be impacted that much by adding a few late game cards into your deck earlier than normal. It's even pretty solid into two of the act 1 elites, so I think you can get away with taking this in the early game.

It definitely wants you to have 4 energy, so that you can immediately benefit from the bonus dexterity, and will feel quite clunky in act 2 if you are still stuck on 3 energy. Great with snecko eye since it's expensive and that gives you a better chance of drawing block cards to combo with the dexterity more frequently. Also great with bolster rod and mummified hand. The upgrade does make the mettalicize effect more reliable, but I don't personally prioritize it until pretty late in the run, since the dexterity is where most of the value is.
